cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Well time to make a start.

Hi Everyone and welcome to today's Precision Club session, in which we'll be taking a look at the Precision 2@H and 2@S Openers, and at the modified 2NT Opening used in my version of Precision.

You can find these on:  ^*h http://bbo.pigpen.org.uk ^*n  You might want to have these onscreen in the background for reference during the session.



|fp|t-title|at|2@H and 2@S Openings|fp||at|^^

Okay, the Precision 2@H and 2@S Openings shows 5-9 points and a 6-card suit.            Note:  5-9  ^*bnot^*n  6-10 

They are weak 2's just like you use when playing Standard American or 2/1.

Ideally, your points should be concentrated in your long suit for greater playing strength, but this is not always able to be the case.

The optimum time to use a weak 2 Opening is, like when pre-empting, when you are 3rd-in-hand after 2 passes.

This is because partner is a passed hand (so you're definitely NOT making life difficult for them) and your Left-hand Opponent is probably a fairly strong hand (so you ARE making life more difficult for THEM!!).|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  The worst position in which to pre-empt is when you are 2nd-in-hand.

Now your RHO is known to be reasonably weak, so you have a 50% chance that it's your PARTNER you are pre-empting rather than your opponents.

1st in hand isn't ideal, but at least now you have only a 33% chance that it's your partner who has a strong hand.

Similarly, pre-empting when 4th-in-hand is normally a bit silly (who are you pre-empting?), UNLESS you have a BURSTING MAXIMUM weak 2 (ie: it's almost intermediate rather than weak).

In this system a 4th-in-hand 2@H or 2@S Opening is treated as GOOD intermediate strength, not weak.

Similarly, having 4-card length in the OTHER Major is sometimes viewed as a minus factor.

I would never say "never" in this regard, though.

If partner HAS already passed then the chances of missing a better contract in the other Major is very low (because if you don't open your weak 2, the chances are that your side side might not get into the bidding at all) but if you are the dealer or 2nd-in-hand I would tend to be more cautious.

3rd-in-hand, after 2 passes, though, (and especially at favourable vulnerability) I would tend to take ANY opportunity to make life difficult for Opps ...so having a poor weak 2 or a 4-card Major alongside it wouldn't stop me What you ought to be a little more careful about is the vulnerability.

Using a Weak 2 Opening at FAVOURABLE vulnerability is the best time (ie: they are vulnerable and you are not) and at Love All is also fine.

At Game All I would be a little more circumspect and it would be a rare occasion indeed that I opened a weak 2 at UNFAVOURABLE vulnerability, when we are vulnerable and they are not.|
